The benefit cost ratio method is one of the engineering economics strategies for comparing designs in terms of cost. The approach is a realistic and well-known method for appraising projects that involves economic analysis of private investment initiatives. The benefit cost ratio is attained via (Kosmadakis et al. 2009):16BCR=UABTAC\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$BCR=\frac{UAB}{TAC}$$\end{document}

The current value of benefit in solar desalination can be gained through the following equation (Shoeibi et al. 2022c):17UAB=K×POW\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$UAB= K\times POW$$\end{document}where POW stands for the price of water, which varies by country and has been 0.28 $ per liter in Egypt. For an investment to be efficient, the benefit-to-cost ratio must be greater than one.

